caption: Victory dance statue Located in the second, less visited part of the Trocadero Gardens, on New York Avenue, at the corner of Rue Albert de Mont in Paris, this statue, made in 1925, honors the goddess Pallas Athenaeus. With his help, the gods defeated the "giants". This work belongs to the Toulouse sculptor Carlo Sarapizoles, who died in Paris in 1971. Beautiful statue
Cool statue in a little park by the Eiffel Tower. Very striking pose of this mythical figure. Nice location to relax in the shade from the crowds as well.
Little statue in a park near Eiffel

A very interesting statue depicting the Triumphal Dance of Pallas Athena, created by one of the most important French sculptors of the 20th century - Carlo Sarrabezolles. The monument was created for the International Exhibition of Modern Decorative and Industrial Art in 1925. The original, made of bronze, is in the museum, and its resin version has been housed in the Jardins du Trocadero in Paris since 1989.

Fan of Greek mythology, I appreciate this statue which corresponds to the image I have of Athena. Having come to see the Eiffel Tower, it was a divine surprise to pass by this sculpture, well located in a small park open 24 hours a day.
Awe and shiver...The triumphant dance of the Goddess Athena after the victory in the battle of giants. When the mind wins the power!!!
